<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by RESULTS UK</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">RESULTS UK </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Now is the moment to act on inclusion of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – the negotiations towards a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">post-2015 development framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> represent a unique opportunity to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reverse the neglect of disability as a core development issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s welcome recent commitments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should be the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">beginning of positioning the UK to lead a revolution in disability-inclusive development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, starting by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">embedding disability as a core part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">FID’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should move in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">careful, phased approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">towards disability-inclusive development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> as part of a wider strategic focus on equity and inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These principles should be embedded throughout DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strategy, structures and processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strategy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">championed at a senior level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflected by the inclusion of disability as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">core requirement of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> country plans, business cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregation of programme plans and results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID should move towards making disability-inclusion a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">requiremen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">t of bilateral and multilateral funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Education should be an early priority for DFID’s inclusive approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The exclusion of di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sabled ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ildren </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">denies their human right to education and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will prevent the world reaching MDG 2. DFID is the leading donor to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education and should lead the way with a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strategic focus on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> equity and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> inclusive education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that benefits all child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ren (not just disabled children). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Inclusive education is the right approach to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strengthening education systems, improving teacher-training and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> delivering better quality education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This should be complemented by additional efforts to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">reach the most marginalised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disabled children out of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An inclusive approach will only become reality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">if implemented on the ground by DFID’s Country Offices </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and in-country partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implementation of central strategy and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">guidance can be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> challenging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID’s devolved structure. Embedding inclusion will require </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strong</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> accountability mechanisms, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">designated leads </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">within country offices, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thorough</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all country advisers, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">substantive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">consultation with Disabled People’s Organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK has a crucial role in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">leading its global partners on inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dialogues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">developing country governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provide an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opportunity to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attitudes toward disability and encourage an incl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">usive education approach. DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should urge the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership for Education to champion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">education for disabled children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and should work with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership on Children with Disabilities, the UN W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ashington Group on Disabilit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">y Statistics, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UNICEF, the World Bank and UNESCO’s Institute for Statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a global </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effort</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to improve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Prime Minister and DFID should continue to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">champion a disability-inclusive post-2015 framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, parti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cularly the “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">no one left behind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” principle, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregation of indicators by disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and the approach that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">no target should be considered met unless for all social groups, including disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The UK is well-positioned to lead on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">post-2015 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership on Disability Data’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About RESULTS UK</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RESULTS is an international grassroots advocacy organization working to generate the public and political will to end hunger and extreme poverty. RESULTS supports a network of volunteer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> across the UK and in five other countries (Australia, Canada, Japan, Mexico and USA). RESULTS works in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partnership with decision-makers, experts and civil society to take effective action and to speak out in favour of anti-poverty measures that really wor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">k. RESULTS UK is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">steering group </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">member of the Global Campaign for Education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(GCE) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BOND Disability and Development Group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide the secretariat to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">APPG on Global Education for All.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Now is the moment to act on inclusion of disabled peo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ple</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disability has long been neglected as a “niche” area of development, deemed by many to be too complex or too small an issue to be core to development efforts. The MDGs fai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">led to mention disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, yet we now know that disabled people make up an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimated 15% of the global population, and that disability is both a cause and a consequence of poverty. 80% of disabled people live in developing countries and the UN calls them “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">the world’s largest minority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Without including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it is cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ear that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">many of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the MDG targets will not be reached</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">led to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a step-change in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recognition of the right</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of disabled people to be included in all aspects of their own development. The UNCRPD also places an obligation on signatories like the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to ensure aid programmes include disabled people</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A major barrier to the recognition of disability as a core devel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opment issue has been the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">appalling lack of data available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Information is often speculative and out of date. A lack of reliable and consistent data at national level feeds a lack of clarity internationally. This has ultimately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">left disabled people invisib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">le, left behind by development efforts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with dramatic improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s in data over recent years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, there is now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">n unprecedented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to bring the needs of disabled people into the light.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Post-2015 n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">egotiations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">represent a unique opportunity to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reverse the neglect of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by ensuring that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the new framework explicitly includes disability as a core issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s recent commitments should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">first step towards the UK leading </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a revolution in disability-inclusive development, starting by embedding disability as a core part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The exclusion of disabled children from education</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RESULTS and our grassroots volunteers have long campaigned for disabled children to have a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ccess to quality education. It is estimated that there are 93 million disabled children globally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and in most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">countries, they are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">more likely to be out of school than any other group of children</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Nepal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it is estimated that 85% of all children out of s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hool are disabled. In Ethiopia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, fewer than 3% of disabled children have access to primary education</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In some countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">being disabled more than doubles the chance of never enrolling in school</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Disabled children are also less likely to remain in school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and transition to the next grade</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he exclusion of disabled children not only denies their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> right to education, but makes it impossible for the world to reach the MDG of universal primary education by 2015. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">57 million children of primary age are st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ill out of school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> around the world and progress all but stalled</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is estimated that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disabled children may make up over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a third of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">out-of-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">school population</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of understanding, negative attitudes and discrimination</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> towards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are major</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> challenges, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> leading parents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in low-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">income countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">hide away their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disabled children</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and leading governments and education decision-makers to segregate disabled children into</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> “special” schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – often inappropriately – which tend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to compound the exclusion from the mainstream and perpetuate the myth that disabled people should be “helped” and not empowered to lead their own productive lives</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disability is also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inextricably linked to other factors which exacerbate exclusion and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nequality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For instance, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ethnic minority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">girls</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> living with disabilities experience triple exclusion. A recent GCE UK report noted that of all the excluding factor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s, disability has the strongest correlation with poor educational outcomes</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Moving DFID tow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ards disability-inclusive development</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The recent commitments made by DFID</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">important and welcome progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and as part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Global Campaign for Education (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> RESULTS has sought to support DFID in this process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The announcement that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">schools built with direct UK support will be built accessibly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an important </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">statement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> developing country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and donor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partners. DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> commitment to work with global partners to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">improve the data and evidence on disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> goes to the heart of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">current invisibility of disabled people. DFID should now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">build on these steps to embed disability-inclusion within its work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and position itself to champion disability-inclusive development with its partners and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the post-2015 dialogue.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RESULTS UK published</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> serious concerns about implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> since then, progress has been made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. At the time, DFID had been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">among</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the first donors to recognise the importance of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">“twin-track” approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which sees the “mainstreaming” o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r inclusion of disabled people in all aspects of their development work (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eg.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensuring education support disabled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">), coupled with additional inputs and resources which recognise the extreme marginalisation of disabled people and go further in suppor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ting them.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID has since put in place </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">useful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">guidance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for its Country Offices</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, despite </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some examples of good practice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID still</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">has no formal framework for the systematic inclusion of disabled people throughout its programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">no formal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">checks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are in place to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID’s work results in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development outcomes for disabled people.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As part of GCE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK, RESULTS UK has raised concern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">implementation remains a real problem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. For instance, in a survey of six Country Offices in 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">012, GCE UK found that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">only half of the offices were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aware of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">guidanc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">only one was implementing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">it</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">later </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report, GCE UK noted that there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">only two mentions of the word “disability” across 14 DFID Country Operational Plans</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. There is substantial risk that the current momentum will be lost unless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">robust implementation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to embed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disability-inclusion within DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should move in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">careful, phased approach towards disability-inclusive development as part of a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> wider strateg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ic focus on equity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that could be similar to its ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Strategic Vision for Girls and Women</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These principles should be embedded throughout DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strateg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, structures and processes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with a high level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prioritisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflected by the inclusion of disability as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">core requirement of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> country plans, business cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and the disaggregation of programme plans and results</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to demonstrate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">how</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID’s work is supporting disabled people. DFID should move towards making disability-i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nclusion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a requirement of bilateral and multilateral funding agreements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, starting with the next cycle of aid reviews.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This strategic focus should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">championed at a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">senior</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The work of Judith Heumann, Special Advisor for International Disability Ri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ghts at the US State Department</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, could provide a useful reference point. Ms Heumann told the APPGs on Disability and Global Education for All in 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> she works closely with USAID to embed disability within their work, with focus on their funding deci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sions, internal processes and training for staff</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The AusAid strategy ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Towards a disability-inclusive Australian aid programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> could also be a helpful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">model</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Inclusive education as a strategic focus for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DFID</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Education should be an early priority for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s inclusive approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, building on the recent commitment on accessible school construction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">largest bilateral donor to basic education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">so has an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opportunity to lead and influence oth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er donors and developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ad the way with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a strategic focus on equity and inclusive education that benefits all children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, particularly the most marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (not just disabled children). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a recent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GCE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> report emphasises</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the UNCRPD established inclusive education as the key mechanism to deliver the right to education for disabled children. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Inclusive education systems can be defined as all children learning together in mainstream classrooms, irrespective of the different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ranges of abilities and disabilities, with teaching methods, materials and school environments that address the needs of all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and additional, individually tailored support as needed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">They can be a powerful tool in addressing inequalities, tackling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> discrimination and changing societal attitudes towards embracing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">diversity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UNICEF notes that inclusive education </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by no means </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a luxury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> available only to the privileged. Rather, examples of inclusion in education can be found in all regions, and challe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nge the notion that such an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach cannot be taken in low resource contexts</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The GCE report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">argues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nclusive education is the right approach to strengthening education systems, improving teacher-training and delivering better quality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nclusive education is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a good</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, enabling developing count</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ry governments to spend limited </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">budgets on a system which benefits all children rather than inefficiently channelled towards a few children in segregated schools (which again reinforces the perception that disability is a cost to the state). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Directly relevant to DFID’s recent commitment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on accessible school construction, UNICEF </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highlights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">costs of integrating accessibility into new buildings can be negligible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (less than 1% of the total cost) compared to the higher cost of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adapting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> completed buildings</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Ultimately, supporting the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education of disabled children will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">yield </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a substantial economic benefit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the developing countries where DFID works</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">leader in supporting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">teacher-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">training</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which is fundamental to meeting MDG 2 and improving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">educational </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">quality</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should match its commitment on accessible school construction with this equally crucial aspect of inclusion, committing that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID will integrate disability and inclusive education throughout the teacher-training it supports</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In line with a “twin trac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">k” approach, DFID should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">put in place additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and resources to support disabled children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID already takes this approach with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gender</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through its ‘Girls Education Challenge’ fund</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could have a dedicated fund to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ojects to r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">each out-of-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">school disabled children; tackle discrimination about disability; and support children with complex needs in community settings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID should take a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cross-sector approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, linking to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">early childhood, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nutrition, health and humanitarian</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> programmes and ensuring that these too are inclusive. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">An inclusive approach will only become reality if implemented on the ground</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RESULTS UK’s experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> suggests that implementation of central strategy and guidance is challenging given DFID’s devolved structure. Embedding inclusion will require </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rong accountability mechanisms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RESULTS UK recommends that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">designated leads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">be identified in DFID’s Cou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ntry Offices to be responsible and accountable for ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">the needs of disabled peop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">le are included in DFID’s work. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">horough training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">on inclusion should be made mandatory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all Country A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">dvisers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As part of GCE UK, RESULTS UK has welcomed discussi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ons with DFID about incorporating disability into ‘continuous professional development’ for Country Advisers, and we urge DFID to proceed with integrating disability and inclusive approaches </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> future training.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Finally, DFID’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s Country O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffices should be r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">equired to engage in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">substantive, regular consultation with Disabled People’s Organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to ensure the participation of disabled people in the planning, implementation and evaluation of programmes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The UK’s role in leading its global partners on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">inclusion</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">dialogues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> with developing country governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to challenge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unhelpful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">attitudes toward disability and encourage an inclusive approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at national level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID should seek to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">build the capacity of national governments t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">o put in place appropriate legislative frameworks and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">deliver</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> ambitious national plans for inclusion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">supported by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">improve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">data on disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In education,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> one systemic barrier is the problem of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">divided ministerial responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">within developing country governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, where education for disabled children is the responsibility of a different ministry than that responsible for the education of non-disabled children</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This division reflects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and reinforces </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the view that the disabled n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eed welfare rather than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">equal access to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often leads to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">segregated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education system with disabled children separated into “special schools”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID should call on national governments to invest in inclusive systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with responsibility for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the education of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clearly within the remit of the Ministry for Education.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use its role on the Board of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership for Education (GPE)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">urge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">GPE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">champion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">inclusive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">education for disabled children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The GPE is the only multilateral partnership devoted to getting all children into</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> school for a quality education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GPE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s unique partnership model, which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coordinates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> donors, civil society and private sector investments in support of nationally-led educa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion plan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, provides an important vehicle for DFID to give global reach to its disability commitments. The GPE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has already committed to supporting disabled children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> its new strategic plan</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">In June 2014, the GPE will hold a replenishment campaign to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> re-galvanise the education community</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with pledges to its fund and commitments to increase domestic financing and bilateral aid to education. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID should use this important moment to call for a global effort to improve support for disabled children’s educa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">play a leading role</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in improving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">data on disability at a global and national level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Progress is already being made through the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Partnership on Children with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and work by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UN Washington</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Group on Disability Statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UNICEF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">World Bank</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UNESCO’s Institute for Statistics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> all have expertise which should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">form part of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a more coordinated effort. Donors like DFID should seek to turn global knowledge-sharing into national action by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">supporting capacity-building within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> national governments and statistical agencies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in developing countries.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">hampioning a disability-inclusive post-2015 framework</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Post-2015 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">negotiations represent a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">once in a lifetime opportunity to reverse the neglect of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Prime Mini</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ster </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has already played an important role as a co-chair of the UN High Level Panel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(HLP) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and has been champion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability-inclusion and the principle of “no one left behind”. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UN High Level Meeting on Disability and Development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in September was the highest level gathering of decision-makers on this issue for many years, and DFID Minister Lynne Featherstone MP’s intervention at this event was widely praised</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We urge DFID to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">continue championing these issues throughout the tough</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> inter-governmental negotiations that lay ahead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We cannot be complacent – with so many priorities on the table, there is a great risk that concepts like ‘disaggregation by disability’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">will be lost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We all have a collective responsibility to ensure that do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es not happen. DFID should fight for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">no one left behind” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">principle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> disaggregation of indicators by disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to measure progress, and the approach that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> no target should be considered met unless for all social groups, including disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">HLP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> called for a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">data revolution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for post-2015</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nowhere is this more needed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> than with disability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The MDGs have resulted in dramatic strides in development data, but disability has been left behind. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e urge the UK Government to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global Pa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">rtnership on Disability Data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” that would bring the needs of disabled people into the light and demand the urgent action </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the UN Secretary-General’s vision of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">a life of dignity for all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> UN Enable (2013), ‘Factsheet on Persons with Disabilities’, </span><a href="http://www.un.org/disabilities/default.asp?id=18"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.un.org/disabilities/default.asp?id=18</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> ‘UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities and Optional Protocol’, Article 32, </span><a href="http://www.un.org/disabilities/documents/convention/convoptprot-e.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.un.org/disabil</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">ities/documents/convention/convoptprot-e.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Global Campaign for Education (2013), ‘Equal Right, Equal Opportunity: Inclusive Education for Children with Disabilities’, </span><a href="http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/reports/Equal%20Right,%20Equal%20Opportunity_WEB.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.campaignforeducation.org/docs/reports/Equal%20Right,%20Equal%20Opportunity_WEB.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-si